<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/swccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Star Wars TCG</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Worst-Case Scenario: Fellowship<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.92)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=4999'>Nathan "Xavier Six" Cardamone</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=4999&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> July 10, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> Weve all been there. The opponent across from us just seems to be on a roll; by like site 3 their fellowship has somehow become a tank division. Each companion is loaded to the teeth with every weapon, armor, shield, tale, etc Its a nightmare. How do you beat an Aragorn who is already a power 13 before power-up events are even played? Gimli with bracers, armor, helm, and an axe shesh, I can deal one wound to him if Im a power 9 and then only if he doesnt toss the bracers to cancel it!  Its ridiculous! But dont fret, there are ways around these problems and besides it could be worse. How much worse? Well, just take a look at this unbelievable fellowship line-up I have dubbed Worst-Case Scenario. Youre not likely to ever actually face something as horrible as these guys but knowing exactly how nasty an opponent can get is always a plus. To make things a bit simpler we are only going to count things that companions can bear themselves, no support area cards, no allies, and no events.  <br>
-----------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
Gimli, the mighty dwarven warrior of the fellowship, as a dwarf he has access to more equipment then any other companion. It is common to see this bruiser other the course of the game pick up armor, a helm, a couple of axes, and maybe even a bracer. Hes a stonewall that most opponents have trouble toppling. So how bad can this guy get? Well with an unheard-of 13 accessories Gimli is pretty much a one man army that can stand up to any minion (even the dreaded Balrog).<br>
<br>
Gimli, Son of Gloin<br>
*Gimlis Helm<br>
*Gimlis Battle Axe<br>
*Dwarven Armor<br>
Dwarven Bracers<br>
Endurance of Dwarves x4<br>
*Hand Axe<br>
*Book of Mazarbul<br>
Elven Cloak<br>
Stone Trolls<br>
Gimlis Pipe<br>
<br>
Power: base(10) max(25) Vitality: 7<br>
<br>
30  75 needed to overwhelm, takes only one wound per battle, may shrug off two wounds, may add one to the archery total once, subtracts one from the minion archery total, Damage +2, Wounds an orc after winning a skirmish, draws an extra card for every dwarf in play after site 3. Can count for 7 pipes in play.<br>
--------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
Arwen, the beautiful and deadly elven princess, is not a true member of the fellowship but still a really valuable addition to any line-up. Arwen with just her sword, stead, and a bow can face down even the nastiest Nazgul.  So how bad can this sweetheart get? Well with her maximum capacity of 9 equipped cards, Arwen is almost an assured victory against any Nazgul, Troll, or Uruk-hai in the area. Not a bad chick to have during the archery phase either.<br>
<br>
Arwen, Daughter of Elrond<br>
Elven Cloak<br>
*Elven Bow<br>
White Arrows of Lorien<br>
The Splendor of Their Banners<br>
*Gwemegil<br>
*Asfaloth<br>
Tale of Gil-galad<br>
Stone Trolls<br>
*No Stranger to Shadows<br>
<br>
Power: base(10) max(23 or more) Vitality: 4<br>
<br>
20-46 needed to overwhelm, Subtracts one from the minion archery total, can add up to 4 to the fellowship archery total, can make the opponent discard up to 6 cards from hand during the archery phase, Damage +1, subtract 1 from the twilight number of each site.<br>
---------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
Boromir, the weak-willed but strong-spirited lord of Gondor, is one of the toughest members of the fellowship. With just his shield and a suit of armor, the lord of Gondor is practically impossible to kill in a fair fight. So how bad is this bad boy? With an amazing 14 items in his inventory, Boromir literally becomes the god of Gondor. Not only is he able to defeat all but the strongest minion, he is virtually immortal as even the nastiest bad guys cant lay a dent in him.<br>
<br>
Boromir, Lord of Gondor<br>
*Blade of Gondor<br>
*Shield of Boromir<br>
Boromirs Cloak<br>
*Flaming Brand<br>
*Armor<br>
*No Stranger to Shadows<br>
Saga of Elendil<br>
*Horn of Boromir<br>
Stone Trolls<br>
Athelas x4<br>
Last Alliance of Elves and Men<br>
<br>
Power: base(10) max(18) Vitality: 4<br>
<br>
39-54 needed to overwhelm, Subtracts one from the minion archery total, may call up allies to fight, Damage +1 or 2, may wound orcs and uruk-hai during skirmishes, Subtracts one from the twilight number of each site, may take only one wound each skirmish phase, minion fighting him gain no strength bonuses from weapons, he may discard weather conditions, may heal up to four wounds<br>
---------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
Aragorn, the man nuf said, is pretty much the best the fellowship has. Aragorn is often the fellowships true offensive force. Wielding his many weapons, few opponent are his equal. So how tough can this champion really get? Well after becoming hopelessly encumbered by his 16 items, Aragorn can potentially defeat any opponent with complete ease even without using pump-up events. <br>
<br>
Aragorn, Heir to the White City<br>
*Rangers Sword<br>
*Aragorns Bow<br>
*Gift of the Evenstar<br>
Elven Cloak<br>
Great Shield<br>
Aragorns Pipe<br>
*Saga of Elendil<br>
Stone Trolls<br>
*No Stranger to Shadows<br>
Athelas x4<br>
*Flaming Brand<br>
*Last Alliance of Elves and Men<br>
*Armor<br>
<br>
Power: base(11) max(19) Vitality: 5<br>
<br>
Takes only one wound per skirmish phase, 28-38 needed to overwhelm, Damage +1 or 2, May wound minions up to 4 times during the archery phase, removes two twilight each fellowship phase, removes one from the twilight number of each site, subtracts 2 from the minion archery total, may heal companions an indefinite number of times with Athelas and pipe, may reduce a minions power by 4 or more.<br>
------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
Gandalf, the mighty wizard, is a one man army with his limitless spells. Gandalf is commonly seen strutting around with ring, staff, and sword. So how all mighty can the wizard become? Actually, Gandalfs maximum equipment comes to only 6 cards. However, the might of these few cards are great as Gandalf is able to weather just about any storm and aid the ringbearer greatly in his burdensome quest. <br>
<br>
Gandalf, Friend of the Shirefolk<br>
*Gandalfs Staff<br>
*Glamdring<br>
*Narya<br>
Elven Cloak<br>
Gandalfs Pipe<br>
Stone Trolls<br>
<br>
Power: base(9) max(15) Vitality: 6<br>
<br>
18-30 need to overwhelm, Subtracts one from minion archery, can remove indefinite number of burdens with Narya and pipe, Damage +1, may look at opponents hand up to 5 times without needing to be healed (this may reduce twilight), May cancel 2 or more skirmishes without the use of healing, reduces cost of each spell by 1<br>
-------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
Frodo, the one true ringbearer, is the humble, but all too important key member of the fellowship. Never without the one ring, Frodo is often seen carrying a vast assortment of gear. So how well guarded can the little guy get? Frodo bearing all 10 of his items is in fact a challenge for even the toughest villains to swat. He is near impossible to kill and can shrug off most assaults. <br>
<br>
Frodo, Old Bilbos Heir<br>
*The One Ring, Isildurs Bane<br>
*Mithril-Coat<br>
*O Elibereth Gilthoniel!<br>
*Sting<br>
Bilbos Pipe<br>
*Bill the Pony<br>
*There and Back Again<br>
Stone Trolls<br>
Elven Cloak<br>
*Phial of Galadriel<br>
<br>
Power: base(7) max(12) Vitality: 5 Resistance: 12<br>
<br>
14-24 needed to overwhelm, may take burdens instead of wounds, may cancel a skirmish involving a Nazgul, may remove the one ring, subtract 2 from the minion archery total, may look at opponents hand up to 4 times without the use of healing (this may reduce twilight), may retrieve discarded hobbit tales, Subtracts one from the twilight number of each site, minions fighting him do not gain strength bonuses from weapons and do not get any damage bonuses, may heal a hobbit ally each turn<br>
-----------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
Legolas, the noble elven prince and archer, is a true blessing to the fellowships ranged attacks. Legolas is often seen wielding nothing more than his favored tale. He isnt commonly used as a fighter. So how powerful can the archer become? With his 8 possible accessories, Legolas is a tour-de-force. Just about as powerful as his kinswoman, Arwen, Legolas brings new meaning to direct damage.  <br>
<br>
Legolas, Greenleaf<br>
Elven Cloak<br>
*Bow of the Galadhrim<br>
White Arrows of Lorien<br>
The Splendor of Their Banners<br>
*Long Knives of Legolas<br>
Asfaloth<br>
*Tale of Gil-galad<br>
Stone Trolls<br>
<br>
Power: base(10) max(17) Vitality: 4<br>
<br>
20-34 needed to overwhelm, may reduce the power of each orc and uruk-hai<br>
Skirmishing him by 2, may wound up to 3 minions during the archery phase or add up to 3 to the archery total or make the opponent discard up to 6 cards from hand, may wound a minion after winning a skirmish, subtracts one from the archery total<br>
------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
Merry, the mighty hobbit, is one half of the force that brought an end to the mighty Witch-King. Merry is almost never seen without a sword or pan in hand and is often carry and certain tale as well. So how strong is the smallest rider of Rohan? With his mere 6 pieces of gear, Merry is just about as tough as hobbits come.<br>
<br>
Merry from Oer the Branywine<br>
*Frying Pan<br>
*There and Back Again<br>
The Gaffers Pipe<br>
Bill the Pony<br>
Stone Trolls<br>
Elven Cloak<br>
<br>
Power: base(6) max(11) Vitality: 4<br>
<br>
12-22 needed to overwhelm, may wound orcs up to 3 times without needing to be healed, may remove an indefinite amount of twilight, Subtracts one from the twilight number of each site, subtracts 1 from the minion archery total <br>
-----------------------------------------------------<br>
Sam, the last resort should Frodo fail, is the possibly the noblest of the fellowship. He is seen in many decks and often plays many different roles. Usually carrying a sword or pan and riding on his trusted pony, Sam is a decent little sccloberr. However, should Frodo perish, Sam is quite the ringbearer in his own right. So how tough is he? Sam fully armed with 9 cards, is nothing to scuff at. His greatest strength comes however from his overall versatility.<br>
<br>
Sam, Proper Poet<br>
*The One Ring, Isildurs Bane<br>
*Frying Pan<br>
*There and Back Again<br>
The Gaffers Pipe<br>
*Bill the Pony<br>
Stone Trolls<br>
Elven Cloak<br>
*O Elibereth Gilthoniel!<br>
*Phial of Galadriel<br>
<br>
Power: base(6) max (11) Vitality: 5 Resistance: 7<br>
<br>
12-22 needed to overwhelm, may wound orcs up to 4 times without the need of healing, may remove an indefinite amount of twilight, Subtracts one from the twilight number of each site, subtracts 1 from the minion archery total, may cancel a skirmish involving a nazgul, may remove the one ring,  may take burdens instead of wounds, may be assigned to 3 minions<br>
---------------------------------------------------- <br>
<br>
Pippen, the curious little hobbit, is the weakest of the fellowship. He sees play only in hobbit decks usually, and even there is often the first companion sacrificed. So how good is he really. Equipped to the max with 6 cards, Pippen is still the frailest of the fellowship<br>
<br>
Pippen, Friend to Frodo<br>
*Hobbit Sword<br>
*There and Back Again<br>
The Gaffers Pipe<br>
Bill the Pony<br>
Stone Trolls<br>
Elven Cloak<br>
<br>
Power: base(5) max(10) Vitality: 4<br>
<br>
10-20 needed to overwhelm, may remove an indefinite amount of twilight, Subtracts one from the twilight number of each site, subtracts 1 from the minion archery total, prevents your hobbit tales from being discarded <br>
---------------------------------------------------------<br>
Well I hope youve enjoyed this look at exactly how nasty the fellowship against you can get. Remember these are worst-case scenarios and I would not recommend playing all of the cards listed in an actual game. Recommended equipment is noted with an *. Also note that the or more listings refer to stats that will normally have the list max number but can potentially have much more (Example: Arwen sword can usually only add 6 power total through the exert and discard feature, however when coupled with Shards of Narsil making your hand larger it can potentially add even more.) Well till next time when I display, Worst-Case Scenario: Shadow.<br>
<br>
